"""
MKT Christ — Luke 10–11
Output: data/commentary/mkt-christ/luke.json

Ch10: Mission of the 72 as harvest/Kingdom-extension; "Johannine thunderbolt"
  (vv.21-22) revealing the mutual Father-Son knowledge; Good Samaritan as
  Christ-the-neighbor; Mary/Martha as the one-necessary-thing.
Ch11: Lord's Prayer as Kingdom-come prayer; ask/seek/knock as prayer-in-Christ;
  Beelzebul/finger-of-God as inaugurated eschatology; sign of Jonah as
  direct resurrection type; lamp/eye; woes on Pharisees.

Classifications: direct=NT cites as fulfilled; type=structural OT anticipation;
  shadow=broader pattern; theme=shared vocabulary; revelation of God=character
  expressed fully in Christ.
"""
import json, pathlib
ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists(): return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    # INTENT: merge new_data into existing without overwriting any present entry
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing: existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]: existing[ch][v] = html

NEW = {
'10': {
'1': '<p>The sending of the seventy-two (or seventy -- textual variant) represents the extension of the messianic mission beyond the Twelve. The seventy recalls the seventy elders of Israel (Num 11:16-17) on whom God placed the Spirit, and the table of nations in Gen 10 (seventy nations in Hebrew tradition, seventy-two in LXX). Either reading points to universality: Jesus is sending workers into a harvest that reaches all peoples. This is the missional foundation for Acts\' Gentile mission -- the twelve apostles extend to Israel; the seventy point toward the nations. The harvest metaphor frames the mission in terms Jesus will use for the final ingathering (Matt 13:39; Rev 14:15).</p>',
'2': '<p>"The harvest is plentiful, but the workers are few. Ask the Lord of the harvest, therefore, to send out workers into his harvest field" -- the harvest metaphor for the gathering of souls (Isa 27:12; Jer 51:33; Joel 3:13; Rev 14:14-16) reaches its fulfillment in Jesus\'s mission. He is the Lord of the harvest who sends the workers -- and the workers are told to ask the Lord of the harvest to send more. The prayer for more workers is addressed to Jesus himself, establishing that Jesus has the authority over the harvest that the OT attributes to YHWH. The prayer creates the feedback loop that generates Acts: the disciples\' prayer produces the Pentecost harvest.</p>',
'3': '<p>"Go! I am sending you out like lambs among wolves" -- the imagery of the sent ones as lambs among wolves draws on Isa 11:6 (the peaceable Kingdom where "the wolf will live with the lamb") and Isa 65:25. In the present age, the sent ones are lambs in a world that has not yet received the Kingdom. The combination of genuine vulnerability ("lambs") and divine commission ("I am sending") frames the missionary vocation: it is not safe but it is authorized. Jesus sends disciples into the condition he himself will face -- the lamb led to slaughter of Isa 53:7.</p>',
'4': '<p>"Do not take a purse or bag or sandals; and do not greet anyone on the road" -- the instruction mirrors Elisha\'s instruction to Gehazi (2 Kgs 4:29: "Don\'t greet anyone you meet") when he was sent urgently to lay Elisha\'s staff on the dead child. The urgency communicates the eschatological moment: the Kingdom is pressing; there is no time for extended social pleasantries. The lack of provisions communicates radical dependence on the Father\'s hospitality provision -- the same dependence Jesus himself models. The absence of provisions is not poverty but eschatological urgency-embodied.</p>',
'5': '<p>"When you enter a house, first say, \'Peace to this house.\'" -- the shalom greeting (peace = wholeness, flourishing, the covenant state of restored relationship with God) is the Kingdom\'s announcement. In Jewish custom, "shalom" was both a greeting and a blessing. In Jesus\'s instruction, the peace pronouncement is not merely a social formality but a Kingdom declaration: the era of shalom that the prophets anticipated (Isa 52:7: "How beautiful on the mountains are the feet of those who bring good news, who proclaim peace") has arrived with the disciples\' mission.</p>',
'6': '<p>"If someone who promotes peace is there, your peace will rest on them; if not, it will return to you" -- "a person of peace" (huios eir&#275;n&#275;s = son of peace) is the one in whom the Kingdom announcement takes root. This prepares the reader for Acts\'s accounts of households receiving the Gospel (Acts 10:2, Cornelius; Acts 16:14-15, Lydia; Acts 16:31-34, the Philippian jailer). The reversible peace -- if rejected it returns to the sender -- establishes that the Gospel announcement creates a division by its reception or rejection, not merely by its proclamation.</p>',
'7': '<p>"The worker deserves his wages" -- cited by Paul in 1 Cor 9:14 and 1 Tim 5:18 as the basis for the church\'s support of its ministers. Jesus establishes this principle at the founding of the mission. The instruction not to move from house to house prevents the kind of social climbing that would compromise the mission\'s integrity. The messenger of the Kingdom is sustained by the Kingdom\'s hospitality, not by accumulating social advantage.</p>',
'8': '<p>Eating whatever is set before you in a town that receives you is the early implicit move toward Gentile table fellowship that Acts 10:9-16 (the vision of unclean animals) and 15:19-21 (the Jerusalem council) will make explicit. The mission\'s table practice anticipates the new covenant community where Jew and Gentile eat together -- the issue Paul addresses in Gal 2:11-14 (the Antioch incident). The instruction to eat what is set before is the proto-practice of the one-new-humanity table that Christ\'s cross creates (Eph 2:14-16).</p>',
'9': '<p>"Heal the sick who are there and tell them, \'The kingdom of God has come near to you.\'" -- the combination of healing and proclamation is the enacted Gospel: the Kingdom comes as both word and deed. The healings are the signs of the Kingdom\'s arrival -- the OT expectation (Isa 35:5-6: "the blind see, the lame walk, the deaf hear") being fulfilled in each town. Jesus is not the only one who enacts these signs; the seventy-two carry the same Kingdom-power because they bear Jesus\'s name and authority. Acts 3:1-10 demonstrates the continuation of this pattern after the resurrection.</p>',
'10': '<p>The towns that reject the mission are to have the Kingdom announced to them nonetheless -- "the kingdom of God has come near" is spoken even over the rejecting town. This anticipates Paul\'s practice of declaring the Gospel even to those who reject it (Acts 13:51; 18:6). The announcement over the refusing town is the last act of grace before judgment is confirmed.</p>',
'11': '<p>"Even the dust of your town we wipe from our feet as a warning to you. Yet be sure of this: the kingdom of God has come near" -- the dust-wiping gesture (practiced by Jews returning from Gentile territory) is here applied to Jewish towns that refuse Jesus\'s messengers. The reversal is stark: towns that receive the seventy are treated as holy space; towns that reject them are treated as spiritually unclean territory. The kingdom\'s arrival makes reception or rejection the decisive criterion of covenant standing, not ethnic identity.</p>',
'12': '<p>"I tell you, it will be more bearable on that day for Sodom than for that town" -- Sodom\'s destruction (Gen 19:24-25) was the paradigmatic divine judgment in the OT. The "that day" is the day of final judgment. Jesus\'s comparison establishes a principle of proportional accountability: greater revelation received and refused = greater judgment incurred. The Incarnation increases human accountability, not merely human opportunity.</p>',
'13': '<p>"Woe to you, Chorazin! Woe to you, Bethsaida!" -- the Gentile cities of Tyre and Sidon (condemned by OT prophets: Isa 23; Ezek 26-28; Joel 3:4-8; Amos 1:9-10) had received no messianic visitation, yet Jesus declares they would have responded better than Chorazin and Bethsaida. This is the logic of the Elijah-Zarephath and Elisha-Naaman examples of 4:25-27: divine mercy is not constrained by covenant boundaries, and covenant privilege does not guarantee covenant response.</p>',
'14': '<p>"But it will be more bearable for Tyre and Sidon at the judgment than for you" -- the judgment comparisons establish a graduated accountability that the NT develops theologically. Heb 10:29 uses the same logic: "How much more severely do you think someone deserves to be punished who has trampled the Son of God underfoot?" The presence of the Son of God creates the highest possible stakes for human response. Every woe here is the Christological argument for human responsibility before the Gospel.</p>',
'15': '<p>"And you, Capernaum, will you be lifted up to the heavens? No, you will go down to Hades" -- the language echoes Isa 14:13-15 (the taunt against Babylon who said "I will ascend to the heavens... I will make myself like the Most High" and was brought down to the realm of the dead). Capernaum\'s sin is ignoring the one greater than Babylon\'s king who has been present in its streets. The pride of privilege -- receiving the Messiah\'s headquarters ministry without genuine response -- is the spiritual equivalent of Babylonian hubris.</p>',
'16': '<p>"Whoever listens to you listens to me; whoever rejects you rejects me; but whoever rejects me rejects him who sent me" -- the chain of identification (disciple to Jesus to Father) establishes the theological principle of apostolic authority. To hear the apostolic proclamation is to hear Jesus; to reject Jesus is to reject the Father. This is the foundation for the NT\'s claim that the Gospel word has divine authority (1 Thess 2:13: "you accepted it not as a human word, but as it actually is, the word of God"). The delegation of divine authority through human messengers is the structural reality of the Incarnation continued in the church\'s mission.</p>',
'17': '<p>"Lord, even the demons submit to us in your name!" -- the authority to cast out demons is delegated authority exercised in Jesus\'s name. The name of Jesus is not a magical formula but the invocation of Jesus\'s identity and authority as the one who has bound the strong man (11:21-22). The disciples\' amazement reveals they did not know in advance the full extent of the authority they had been given. Acts 16:18 (Paul commanding a spirit to leave "in the name of Jesus Christ") demonstrates the continuation of this delegated authority after the resurrection.</p>',
'18': '<p>"I saw Satan fall like lightning from heaven" -- the statement is eschatologically momentous. Whether Jesus refers to a primordial fall (Isa 14:12), the present defeat of Satan through the seventy-two\'s mission, or the coming cross-defeat (John 12:31: "Now the prince of this world will be driven out"), the implication is the same: the Incarnation and the mission that flows from it constitutes the decisive reversal of Satan\'s cosmic authority. Rev 12:7-12 presents this fall as the cosmic consequence of the Christ-event.</p>',
'19': '<p>"I have given you authority to trample on snakes and scorpions and to overcome all the power of the enemy" -- the authority over serpents and scorpions draws on Ps 91:13 and on the Gen 3:15 promise: "I will put enmity between you and the woman... you will strike his heel." The mission of the seventy-two is part of the unfolding fulfillment of Gen 3:15 -- the seed of the woman crushing the serpent\'s head. The psalm the devil quoted in the temptation (4:10-11) is now fulfilled in the disciples\' mission.</p>',
'20': '<p>"Do not rejoice that the spirits submit to you, but rejoice that your names are written in heaven" -- the eschatological book of the living (Exod 32:32-33; Dan 12:1; Mal 3:16; Rev 3:5; 20:12) is the final register of the saved. Jesus redirects the seventy-two\'s joy from the temporary (victory over demons in the present age) to the permanent (salvation, the eternal state). The Christ-centered priority: not power demonstrations but the relationship with the Father that secures eternal life.</p>',
'21': '<p>"I praise you, Father, Lord of heaven and earth, because you have hidden these things from the wise and learned, and revealed them to little children" -- Luke\'s "Johannine thunderbolt" (Matt 11:25-27 || Luke 10:21-22) is the most explicitly trinitarian passage in the Synoptics. Jesus addresses the Father with the Hebrew intimacy term "Abba" while using the full cosmic title "Lord of heaven and earth." The revelation to "little children" (n&#275;piois = infants/those without status) vs. the concealment from "the wise" is the epistemological pattern of the Incarnation: the Gospel is received by those who have no self-sufficient wisdom to resist it.</p>',
'22': '<p>"All things have been committed to me by my Father. No one knows who the Son is except the Father, and no one knows who the Father is except the Son and those to whom the Son chooses to reveal him" -- this verse claims mutual exclusive knowledge between Father and Son that in the OT is reserved for YHWH\'s own self-knowledge (Isa 46:9-10; 55:8-9). Jesus claims to be the exclusive mediator of the Father\'s revelation. John 14:6 ("no one comes to the Father except through me") is the direct application. This is the Christological pinnacle of the Synoptic tradition.</p>',
'23': '<p>"Blessed are the eyes that see what you see" -- beatitude pronounced on the disciples as witnesses of the Kingdom\'s arrival. The Christological point: the disciples are in the position that all of OT history was pointing toward. Abraham, Moses, David, Isaiah, and the prophets were living in the promise; the disciples are living in the fulfillment. 1 Pet 1:10-12 makes this explicit: "the prophets who spoke of the grace that was to come to you... tried to find out the time and circumstances to which the Spirit of Christ in them was pointing."</p>',
'24': '<p>"Many prophets and kings desired to see what you see but did not see it" -- the prophets\' desire to see the Christ was the desire of the entire OT canonical horizon. Heb 11:13: "All these people were still living by faith when they died. They did not receive the things promised; they only saw them and welcomed them from a distance." David himself saw it prophetically (Acts 2:30-31: "he was a prophet and knew that God had promised him on oath that he would place one of his descendants on his throne"). The disciples stand where history had been aiming.</p>',
'25': '<p>"What must I do to inherit eternal life?" -- the question frames the Good Samaritan parable within the question of salvation. The lawyer\'s use of "inherit" draws on the OT inheritance-language: Israel inherits the land (Num 26:55-56; Deut 4:21); the righteous inherit the kingdom (Ps 37:11; Matt 5:5). Jesus turns the question back to the Law, then to the lawyer\'s application, then tells a parable that redefines who is the neighbor -- and implicitly, who is the one who genuinely fulfills the law\'s demand.</p>',
'26': '<p>"What is written in the Law? How do you read it?" -- Jesus characteristically responds to a question with a question. The lawyer\'s citation of the Shema (Deut 6:5) plus Lev 19:18 as the summary of the Law anticipates Jesus\'s own summary in Matt 22:37-40. The Christological point: Jesus himself is the perfect embodiment of both commands -- complete love for the Father and complete love for neighbor, supremely demonstrated at the cross.</p>',
'27': '<p>The fourfold "all" (heart / soul / strength / mind) is the total-person demand of the Shema. No division of the person is exempt from the love-obligation. Jesus is not modifying the Law but affirming its deepest demand -- a demand that no human perfectly fulfills, which is precisely why the one who perfectly fulfills it (Christ) must do so on humanity\'s behalf.</p>',
'28': '<p>"Do this and you will live" -- the conditional response is true as stated: love God and neighbor completely = life. But it conceals the problem: who can do this completely? The subsequent parable exposes the gap through the lawyer\'s question "who is my neighbor?" Paul makes the same point in Gal 3:12: "The law is not based on faith; on the contrary, it says, \'The person who does these things will live by them.\'" The Law\'s "do this and live" is real -- but the impossibility of doing it drives the Law\'s function as a schoolmaster pointing to Christ (Gal 3:24).</p>',
'29': '<p>"And who is my neighbor?" -- the question was a live legal debate. The lawyer\'s motive ("wanting to justify himself") reveals the heart: not a genuine question but a limiting move, a desire to draw the boundary of obligation narrowly enough to be able to claim fulfillment. The Good Samaritan parable answers the question by inverting it: Jesus does not define who counts as a neighbor but asks which person acted as a neighbor. The question is not "who deserves my love?" but "whose love do you need?" Christ himself is the one who loved those who did not deserve it.</p>',
'30': '<p>A man going down from Jerusalem to Jericho, robbed, beaten, and left half-dead. The parable\'s Christological typological reading (from Origen through Augustine): the wounded man is Adam/humanity; the priest and Levite are the Law and the sacrificial system that cannot save; the Samaritan is Christ who crosses every barrier to help. Whether or not the allegory was intended, the Christological resonance is real: only the despised outsider, the one the religious leaders avoid, provides the rescue. The esplagchnisth&#275; (was moved with compassion: v.33) is the term used for Jesus\'s own compassion throughout the Gospels.</p>',
'31': '<p>The priest who "passed by on the other side" -- likely concerned with ritual purity (contact with a half-dead person would disqualify a priest for temple service under Lev 21:1-4). The priest\'s passage represents the inability of the Levitical system to address the fundamental human wound. Heb 7:11-12 makes the theological point: "if perfection could have been attained through the Levitical priesthood... why was there still need for another priest?" The Law\'s priest cannot complete the rescue that humanity needs. A better priest has come.</p>',
'32': '<p>The Levite likewise "passed by on the other side" -- the double failure of the cultic system is the parable\'s first Christological move. The religious-cultic professionals who should be the agents of mercy cannot provide it. The Law can define the obligation ("love your neighbor") but it cannot produce the neighbor-love. Only a transformed heart (Jer 31:33: "I will put my law in their minds and write it on their hearts") can produce genuine neighbor-love.</p>',
'33': '<p>"But a Samaritan... when he saw him, he took pity on him" -- the Samaritan as hero is a provocation in the context of Jewish-Samaritan enmity (John 4:9). The Christological typological reading: Jesus himself is the despised one (John 8:48: "Are we not right in saying that you are a Samaritan and demon-possessed?") who crosses barriers of ethnic and religious hostility to rescue the wounded. "He took pity" (esplagchnisth&#275; = was moved in his bowels, the deepest compassion) is the term used for Jesus\'s own compassion throughout the Gospels (7:13; 15:20).</p>',
'34': '<p>The Samaritan\'s specific acts: oil (healing) and wine (cleansing), the animal (giving up his own comfort), the inn (providing ongoing shelter), the personal care through the night. The Christological reading of the oil and wine: the oil of anointing (the Messiah = the anointed one) and the wine of the new covenant (22:20: "this cup is the new covenant in my blood"). The Samaritan\'s rescue is an enacted image of the atonement: the self-giving descent of the one who could have passed by, to lift up the one who cannot lift himself.</p>',
'35': '<p>"When I return, I will reimburse you for any extra expense you may have" -- the promissory element of the rescue: the rescue is not complete at the initial intervention but requires ongoing provision and a promised return. The Christological typological reading (Augustine): the inn = the church; the innkeeper = the church\'s ministers; the two denarii = the provisions of Word and sacrament; the promised return = the Second Coming. The mapping carries genuine theological weight regardless of whether Jesus intended every detail allegorically.</p>',
'36': '<p>"Which of these three do you think was a neighbor to the man who fell into the hands of robbers?" -- Jesus inverts the original question (v.29: "who is my neighbor?") into a question about enacted neighborliness. The lawyer asked "who counts as my neighbor?" -- a definitional question designed to limit obligation. Jesus asks "which one acted as a neighbor?" -- a volitional question that reframes obligation as action. Christ himself is the answer to the second question: the one who acted as neighbor to humanity when humanity could not act for itself.</p>',
'37': '<p>"Go and do likewise" -- the command is not achievable by moral effort alone but by the Spirit that Christ sends. Paul writes that "love is the fulfillment of the law" (Rom 13:10) and that the Spirit who produces this love is "poured out into our hearts" (Rom 5:5). The "go and do likewise" is the Law\'s demand fulfilled in Christ and then enabled in those who receive his Spirit. The Good Samaritan parable ends not with a definition but with a commission: be what Christ is toward the world.</p>',
'38': '<p>Martha opening her home to Jesus during the Jerusalem journey is an act of significant generosity and hospitality (philoxenia = love of strangers: Heb 13:2). The conflict that follows is not about hospitality vs. neglect but about priority of attention: between serving the Lord and sitting at his feet. Both are genuine goods; the question is their right order.</p>',
'39': '<p>"Mary, who sat at the Lord\'s feet listening to what he said" -- sitting at the teacher\'s feet was the formal posture of a disciple (Acts 22:3: Paul educated "under Gamaliel"). A woman sitting at a rabbi\'s feet as a disciple was unconventional. "Listening to what he said" uses the singular "word" (logos): Mary is receiving the Word of God that Jesus embodies and speaks. The posture anticipates the "one necessary thing" Jesus will identify.</p>',
'40': '<p>Martha "was distracted by all the preparations" (periespa&#333;to peri poll&#275;n diakonian = was being pulled around in many directions of service) -- diakonia (service/ministry) is significant: Martha\'s service is genuinely ministry. Luke uses diakonein/diakonia throughout Luke-Acts for significant service. Martha\'s complaint to Jesus reveals an anxiety about the service that transforms it from gift to burden. The distracting "many things" are contrasted with the "one thing" that Jesus will identify.</p>',
'41': '<p>"Martha, Martha, you are worried and upset about many things" -- the doubled name signals urgent personal concern, not rebuke. The anxiety (merimnas) is the same word used in the parable of the sower (8:14: "choked by life\'s worries") and in the prohibition of worry (12:22-31). The many things (pollon) contrast with the one thing (henos, v.42): Martha has allowed the multiplicity of service to obscure the singular priority that makes all service meaningful.</p>',
'42': '<p>"Mary has chosen what is better, and it will not be taken away from her" -- the "one thing necessary" (henos de estin chreia) is sitting at Jesus\'s feet in the posture of a disciple receiving the Word. The promise "it will not be taken away from her" is the eschatological permanence of the better portion: the Kingdom received through hearing is permanent; everything else is temporary. This anticipates the one thing Paul counts as supreme gain (Phil 3:8: "knowing Christ Jesus my Lord"). All service flows from and returns to this foundation.</p>',
},
'11': {
'1': '<p>The disciples\' request to be taught to pray "as John taught his disciples" places Jesus in the tradition of prayer-instruction that characterized Israel\'s great teachers. Moses taught Israel to pray (Deut 9:25-29); the Psalms gave Israel corporate prayer-language. The Lord\'s Prayer that follows is not merely a private devotion but the Kingdom prayer -- the prayer that asks for the eschatological realities Jesus has come to inaugurate: the Father\'s name honored, the Kingdom arrived, the daily bread provided, debts forgiven, deliverance from trial.</p>',
'2': '<p>"Father, hallowed be your name, your kingdom come" -- the address "Father" (Pater) establishes the prayer in the relational context that Jesus opened in 10:21-22: the Father-Son intimacy that the disciples share through Jesus. "Hallowed be your name" draws on the Kaddish prayer: "May His great name be sanctified." "Your kingdom come" is the eschatological petition for the reign that Jesus announced (4:43; 8:1; 9:2) to arrive in its fullness. The entire prayer is Christological: only in and through Christ does the Father\'s name find its supreme hallowing and the Kingdom come.</p>',
'3': '<p>"Give us each day our daily bread" -- the daily provision petition draws on the manna typology: God provided "daily bread" in the wilderness, each day\'s portion and no more (Exod 16:4, 19-20). The "daily" rhythm of dependence on the Father is the prayer-enactment of the trust Jesus embodies. Jesus himself is the fulfillment of the manna type: John 6:35 ("I am the bread of life; whoever comes to me will never go hungry"). To pray for daily bread is to pray for Christ himself, the sustenance of every day.</p>',
'4': '<p>"Forgive us our sins, for we also forgive everyone who sins against us. And lead us not into temptation" -- the forgiveness petition connects to the Good Samaritan parable\'s mercy (10:37) and to the Lord\'s payment of the wounded man\'s debt (10:35). The "lead us not into temptation" (m&#275; eisenenk&#275;is h&#275;mas eis peirasmon) echoes Jesus\'s own instruction in Gethsemane (22:40, 46) -- the prayer that the disciples failed to pray there. The Lord\'s Prayer is the prayer for Gethsemane-faithfulness before the Gethsemane arrives.</p>',
'5': '<p>The parable of the friend at midnight (vv.5-8) follows the Lord\'s Prayer as an illustration of the ask/seek/knock principle. The parable\'s logic: if a sleeping neighbor will eventually provide bread because of the requester\'s persistence, how much more will the heavenly Father who is awake and attentive provide what his children need? The parable is a kal vachomer argument: the human father\'s eventual generosity is the minimum guarantee; the heavenly Father\'s generosity is the maximum reality.</p>',
'6': '<p>"Because a friend of mine on a journey has come to me, and I have nothing to set before him" -- the hospitality obligation driving the midnight request is the petitioner asking not for his own needs but for the resources to honor his obligation to another. This anticipates the intercessory nature of prayer: praying not only for oneself but for others, carrying others\' needs before the Father.</p>',
'7': '<p>"I can\'t get up and give you anything" -- the obstacle to the provision is not the neighbor\'s unwillingness but inconvenience. Luke\'s parable contains a resistant character who eventually relents: the same structure as the unjust judge of 18:1-8. The resistant character is not an image of God (God is not reluctant to give) but a contrast: if even a resistant human neighbor eventually provides, the willing Father certainly will.</p>',
'8': '<p>"Because of your shameless audacity (anaideia) he will surely get up and give you as much as you need" -- anaideia (shamelessness, holy boldness, persistence without embarrassment) is the quality commended. Not the quality of the provider but of the petitioner. To pray with shameless persistence is to refuse to take "not yet" as "no." The Christological foundation: Jesus\'s own prayer in Gethsemane (22:44: "praying more earnestly") is the model of shameless persistence in the face of the most severe trial.</p>',
'9': '<p>"Ask and it will be given to you; seek and you will find; knock and the door will be opened to you" -- the three imperatives (keep asking, keep seeking, keep knocking) form a chiasm with their responses and together constitute the theology of petition-prayer. The promises are absolute: it WILL be given, you WILL find, the door WILL be opened. The basis for this certainty is the Father\'s character, established in vv.11-13. The prayer confidence flows from Christology: because of who Jesus is, the disciples have access to the Father (John 14:13-14; 16:23-24: "ask in my name").</p>',
'10': '<p>"For everyone who asks receives; the one who seeks finds; and to the one who knocks, the door will be opened" -- the universal application ("everyone who asks") establishes that the prayer promises are not for an elite but for all who come in faith. Because the promise is certain, persistence is the appropriate response to apparent delay. Rom 8:32: "He who did not spare his own Son, but gave him up for us all -- how will he not also, along with him, graciously give us all things?" The Father who gave the Son will not withhold lesser gifts.</p>',
'11': '<p>"Which of you fathers, if your son asks for a fish, will give him a snake instead?" -- the analogy from human fatherhood to divine fatherhood establishes the argument. The Father-child relationship is the structural analogy between human and divine provision. Jesus has opened this relationship in 10:21-22: the Father he knows as "Father" is now the Father to whom the disciples pray. The prayer promises are secured by the quality of the Father\'s character, not by the quality of the disciples\' requesting.</p>',
'12': '<p>"Or if he asks for an egg, will give him a scorpion?" -- the snake and scorpion echo v.19 of the previous chapter: "I have given you authority to trample on snakes and scorpions." The Father does not give his children what harms them but what helps them. The deceptive provision (something that looks like food but kills) is what the evil one gives, not what the Father gives. This establishes the contrast between divine generosity and satanic deception that structures Luke 11.</p>',
'13': '<p>"How much more will your Father in heaven give the Holy Spirit to those who ask him!" -- the answer to "what is the best gift the Father gives?" is specifically "the Holy Spirit." The Holy Spirit is the eschatological gift of the new covenant (Ezek 36:27; Joel 2:28-29) -- the gift that the risen Jesus sends (Acts 2:33: "he has received from the Father the promised Holy Spirit and has poured out what you now see and hear"). Prayer for the Holy Spirit is prayer for the full arrival of the new covenant. Luke emphasizes the Spirit throughout as the gift that Jesus promises and the resurrection gives.</p>',
'14': '<p>Jesus casting out a mute demon -- the healing of mutes is a Messianic sign (Isa 35:6: "the mute tongue will shout for joy"; Matt 9:32-33; 12:22-23). The crowd divides immediately: some attribute the exorcism to Beelzebul; some demand a sign from heaven. The division that Jesus\'s presence creates is the crisis of eschatological decision -- you cannot remain neutral before the Kingdom\'s arrival. This division anticipates the final separation of the judgment.</p>',
'15': '<p>"By Beelzebul, the prince of demons, he is driving out demons" -- the Beelzebul accusation (Baal-Zebul = "lord of the flies" or "lord of the high place," a Philistine deity: 2 Kgs 1:2-3) is the worst possible reading of Jesus\'s exorcisms: deliberate attribution of divine work to satanic power. Matt 12:31-32 connects this accusation to the blasphemy against the Holy Spirit. The accusation is not a failure of information but a failure of will: those who see the Kingdom\'s power and attribute it to Satan have hardened themselves against the very evidence that could change them.</p>',
'16': '<p>"Others tested him by asking for a sign from heaven" -- the demand for more signs is the posture of unbelief: "If I saw enough signs I would believe" is always false -- there will always be room for one more required sign. Jesus has already said (10:13-15) that the miracles performed in Chorazin and Bethsaida were sufficient to produce repentance in Tyre and Sidon. The problem is not the quantity or quality of evidence but the condition of the heart. Only the sign of Jonah will be given (vv.29-32).</p>',
'17': '<p>Jesus\'s counter-argument: "Any kingdom divided against itself will be ruined" -- the internal-division argument refutes the Beelzebul charge logically. The exorcisms are evidence of kingdom-conflict, not kingdom-cooperation. The divided-kingdom axiom is universally valid: Satan is not in the business of losing ground; Jesus is. The Beelzebul charge fails its own logical test, exposing it as motivated reasoning rather than honest evaluation.</p>',
'18': '<p>"If Satan is divided against himself, how can his kingdom stand?" -- if Jesus is a Beelzebul-agent, then Satan is committing strategic self-destruction -- an absurdity. The reference to "your people" who also practice exorcism (cf. Acts 19:13-14: Jewish exorcists) is the tu quoque response: by what power do they cast out demons? The Pharisees cannot condemn Jesus\'s exorcisms without also condemning their own tradition\'s practice.</p>',
'19': '<p>"Now if I drive out demons by Beelzebul, by whom do your followers drive them out? So then, they will be your judges" -- the "they will be your judges" (autoi hym&#333;n kritai esontai) is an eschatological statement: the disciples of the Pharisees who practice exorcism will condemn the Pharisees\' rejection of the one who demonstrates the same power definitively. The judgment comes from the Pharisees\' own tradition turned against them.</p>',
'20': '<p>"But if I drive out demons by the finger of God (en daktyl&#333; theou), then the kingdom of God has come upon you" -- the "finger of God" is the decisive phrase. In Exod 8:19, the Egyptian magicians see Moses\' works and declare: "This is the finger of God." The Sinai tablets were written "by the finger of God" (Exod 31:18; Deut 9:10). Jesus claims that his exorcisms carry the same divine signature as the Exodus miracles. And the conclusion: the Kingdom has "come upon" (ephthasen eph\' hymas = has already arrived, reached you) -- not merely "is near" but has actually arrived in the person of Jesus.</p>',
'21': '<p>"When a strong man, fully armed, guards his own house, his possessions are safe" -- the "strong man" identifies Satan as the cosmic householder who has maintained control over the human domain since the Fall. The "possessions" (ta hyparchonta) are the human beings who are "bound" by Satan (13:16). Before Jesus\'s coming, Satan\'s house was not being contested. The arrival of Jesus constitutes the entry of the stronger man who will plunder the strong man\'s goods.</p>',
'22': '<p>"But when someone stronger attacks and overpowers him, he takes away the armor in which the man trusted and divides up his plunder" -- Jesus is the stronger one (ischyroteros; cf. John the Baptist\'s language: 3:16: "one more powerful than I is coming"). The cross is the decisive battle: Col 2:15: "having disarmed the powers and authorities, he made a public spectacle of them, triumphing over them by the cross." Heb 2:14-15: "by his death he might break the power of him who holds the power of death -- that is, the devil." The plunder is the redeemed: those freed from Satan\'s household to become the Father\'s children.</p>',
'23': '<p>"Whoever is not with me is against me, and whoever does not gather with me scatters" -- the binary statement allows no middle position in the Kingdom conflict. The gathering/scattering language draws on the OT\'s shepherd imagery: YHWH gathers the scattered sheep of Israel (Ezek 34:12-16; Zech 10:8-10). Jesus gathers as YHWH gathers -- and those who refuse to join the gathering actively contribute to the scattering. There is no neutrality in the eschatological conflict between Christ and the adversary.</p>',
'24': '<p>"When an impure spirit comes out of a person, it goes through arid places seeking rest" -- the return of the unclean spirit illustrates the inadequacy of moral reformation without new creation. Exorcism without the Spirit\'s occupancy leaves the person worse off. The Christological application: the reception of Jesus must be complete -- not merely the expulsion of the old but the indwelling of the new (John 14:16-17: "I will ask the Father, and he will give you another advocate... he will be in you").</p>',
'25': '<p>"It finds the house swept clean and put in order" -- the swept and ordered house is outwardly reformed without being spiritually transformed. This is the state of those who have experienced something of Jesus\'s power without receiving him through faith. The house that is swept but not occupied by the Spirit of Jesus is available for the enemy\'s return. Reformation without regeneration -- moral improvement without the indwelling Spirit -- is spiritually dangerous.</p>',
'26': '<p>"Then it goes and takes seven other spirits more wicked than itself, and the final condition of that person is worse than the first" -- the sevenfold escalation of spiritual bondage for those who experienced deliverance but did not remain with Jesus is the warning against treating the Gospel as a moral improvement program. Heb 6:4-6 and 10:26-31 use the same logic for those who have received the Gospel and then turned away from it. The stakes of encountering Christ and not receiving him are higher than never encountering him at all.</p>',
'27': '<p>"Blessed is the mother who gave you birth and nursed you" -- the beatitude on Jesus\'s mother is a common form of honor-praise. The exclamation is sincere but incomplete: physical kinship with Jesus is not the basis of blessing. Mary herself is blessed not merely because she bore Jesus but because she believed (1:45: "Blessed is she who has believed that the Lord would fulfill his promises to her"). The beatitude is true but needs to be redirected by Jesus\'s response.</p>',
'28': '<p>"Blessed rather are those who hear the word of God and obey it" -- Jesus\'s response redefines the ground of blessing. Mary\'s true blessedness is exactly that she heard the word of God and kept it (her Magnificat, 1:46-55, proves this). The "rather" (menounge) expands the circle: any and all who hear and obey the word of God share in the blessing that Mary exemplified. James 1:22-25 develops this: be doers of the word, not merely hearers. The relationship with Jesus that matters is not biological proximity but hearing and keeping his word.</p>',
'29': '<p>"This is a wicked generation. It asks for a sign, but none will be given it except the sign of Jonah" -- the sign of Jonah is the only sign Jesus will give. Jonah\'s three days in the belly of the great fish (Jon 1:17) is the type of Jesus\'s three days in the earth. Matt 12:40 makes the typology explicit: "For as Jonah was three days and three nights in the belly of a huge fish, so the Son of Man will be three days and three nights in the heart of the earth." The death-and-resurrection event is the definitive sufficient sign: those who reject the resurrection reject the only sign that matters.</p>',
'30': '<p>"For as Jonah was a sign to the Ninevites, so also will the Son of Man be to this generation" -- Jonah as type of Christ: Jonah came from the "dead" (from the fish\'s belly = death\'s domain) and preached to the Gentile city that repented. Jesus will come from the dead (the resurrection) and his preaching will reach the nations. The sign-demanding generation will be judged by the response of the Ninevites who repented at Jonah\'s word. The missionary logic of Acts -- Paul going to the Gentiles because Israel rejected the Gospel -- is anticipated here.</p>',
'31': '<p>"The Queen of the South will rise at the judgment with the people of this generation and condemn them, for she came from the ends of the earth to listen to Solomon\'s wisdom, and now something greater than Solomon is here" -- the Queen of Sheba (1 Kgs 10:1-10) traveled 2,400 km to hear Solomon\'s wisdom. Jesus is "greater than Solomon" (pl&#275;on Solomonos h&#333;de): Solomon\'s wisdom was given; Jesus is divine Wisdom incarnate (1 Cor 1:24: "Christ the power of God and the wisdom of God"; John 1:1-3). The Christological escalation: from type (Solomon) to antitype (the Son of Man, wisdom incarnate).</p>',
'32': '<p>"The people of Nineveh will stand up at the judgment with this generation and condemn it, for they repented at the preaching of Jonah; and now something greater than Jonah is here" -- Jonah was a reluctant prophet who delivered a five-word message and the entire city repented. Jesus has been preaching the Kingdom, healing the sick, raising the dead, casting out demons -- and the sign-demanding generation refuses. "Something greater than Jonah is here": the one whom Jonah typified has arrived, and the type\'s fulfillment demands a proportionally greater response.</p>',
'33': '<p>"No one lights a lamp and puts it in a place where it will be hidden, or under a bowl. Instead they put it on its stand" -- the lamp placed on a stand is the proper proclamation of the Kingdom. The light-metaphor for the Messiah runs from Isa 9:2 through Isa 42:6 and 49:6 to Simeon\'s canticle (2:32: "a light for revelation to the Gentiles"). Jesus is the lamp -- placed in the public square of Israel\'s history for all to see. The hiding of a lamp is the rejection of this light.</p>',
'34': '<p>The "healthy eye" (ophthalmos haplos = simple/single/sound eye) and the "unhealthy eye" (poneros = evil/bad eye) use the Jewish idiom where "good eye" = generosity and "evil eye" = greed or envy (Matt 6:22-23; Prov 22:9; 23:6). The lamp/eye/body passage follows the "greater than Jonah/Solomon" sayings: the Christological light has been set on the stand; the question is whether the eye (the receptive faculty) is sound enough to receive it. Those who demand signs have an "evil eye" -- their receptive faculty is damaged by self-interest.</p>',
'35': '<p>"See to it, then, that the light within you is not darkness" -- the warning to test one\'s own light is Christological self-examination. The "light within" is either genuine light received from Christ (2 Cor 4:6: "God... made his light shine in our hearts to give us the light of the knowledge of God\'s glory displayed in the face of Christ") or a false light that is actually darkness. Those who believe themselves to be enlightened guides may be the most profoundly in the dark. The self-examination demanded is whether one\'s "seeing" (response to Jesus) is based on genuinely received light.</p>',
'36': '<p>"If your whole body is full of light, and no part of it dark, it will be just as full of light as when a lamp shines its light on you" -- the state of complete illumination is the state of those who have fully received the light of Christ. No dark parts = complete discipleship, full surrender to the Word. The image anticipates the New Jerusalem of Rev 21:23-24: "The city does not need the sun or the moon to shine on it, for the glory of God gives it light, and the Lamb is its lamp." The fully illuminated body is the eschatological goal of sanctification.</p>',
'37': '<p>Jesus\'s willingness to eat with Pharisees (7:36; 11:37; 14:1) demonstrates that his criticism of Pharisaism is not personal animosity but prophetic challenge. He goes where invited; he does not refuse the table of those he will confront. The prophetic tradition has always been willing to speak truth in the face of power from within the host\'s own house.</p>',
'38': '<p>"The Pharisee was surprised that he had not first washed before the meal" -- ritual hand-washing before meals (netilat yadayim: m. Yadayim 1:1-5) was the Pharisaic standard. Jesus\'s non-compliance creates the opportunity for the woe-discourse. Instead of defending his practice, he challenges the Pharisee\'s entire framework: the hand-washing controversy is the entry point to the deeper question of internal vs. external purity -- the Christological distinction between the old covenant\'s external ritual and the new covenant\'s interior transformation (Jer 31:33).</p>',
'39': '<p>"You Pharisees clean the outside of the cup and dish, but inside you are full of greed and wickedness" -- the cup/dish imagery contrasts ritual purity (Pharisaic concern with vessel cleanliness: m. Kelim 25:1-9) with moral purity. The internal/external contrast is a new-covenant announcement: Jeremiah\'s promise of a law "written on the heart" (Jer 31:33) and Ezekiel\'s promise of a new spirit within (Ezek 36:26-27) point toward the interior transformation that ritual cleansing cannot achieve.</p>',
'40': '<p>"You foolish people! Did not the one who made the outside make the inside also?" -- the Creator argument: God who made the inside of the cup also made the inside of the person. To clean the outside and ignore the inside is to act as if God were only concerned with the exterior -- which is precisely the mistake the Pharisaic system enabled. The God who demands complete love (10:27) is not satisfied with external compliance. He made the inside, and he requires the inside.</p>',
'41': '<p>"Give what is inside to the poor, and everything will be clean for you" -- the alternative to ritual cleanness is interior generosity. "Give what is inside" (ta enonta = the things within) to the poor = the inside-out purity Jesus commends. The connection between inner cleanness and care for the poor runs from Isa 58:6-7 through James 1:27 ("Religion that God our Father accepts as pure and faultless is this: to look after orphans and widows in their distress").</p>',
'42': '<p>"Woe to you Pharisees, because you give God a tenth of your mint, rue and all other kinds of garden herbs, but you neglect justice and the love of God" -- meticulous attention to religious detail as a cover for the neglect of justice and the love of God. The prophetic tradition makes the same critique: Amos 5:21-24; Isa 1:11-17; Mic 6:6-8. Jesus does not condemn the tithing but exposes it as a substitute for justice and covenant-love. The woe is not against piety but against piety that has replaced its own foundation.</p>',
'43': '<p>"Woe to you Pharisees, because you love the most important seats in the synagogues and respectful greetings in the marketplaces" -- the pursuit of public honor contradicts the Kingdom\'s principle of status-inversion (9:48: "the one who is least among you all is the greatest"). The Pharisees have oriented their public religion toward human honor rather than divine honor. The contrast with Jesus who "humbled himself" (Phil 2:8) and "made himself nothing" (Phil 2:7) is the Christological standard they miss.</p>',
'44': '<p>"Woe to you, because you are like unmarked graves, which people walk over without knowing it" -- under Num 19:16, a person who walked over a grave was made ritually unclean. An unmarked grave contaminates the unsuspecting passerby without warning. The Pharisees\' outward respectability conceals a moral and spiritual contamination that defiles those who follow their guidance. The Christological contrast: Jesus makes the unclean clean (5:13), not the one who contaminates those who approach.</p>',
'45': '<p>An expert in the law protests: "You insult us also" -- the lawyers are the specialists who encoded the system Jesus has been critiquing. Jesus does not apologize but extends the woes to cover the lawyers specifically. Their role as interpreters of Scripture makes their failure more culpable: they are the gatekeepers of the very revelation that points to Christ, using their interpretive authority to obstruct rather than open the way.</p>',
'46': '<p>"Woe to you, because you load people down with burdens they can hardly carry, and you yourselves will not lift one finger to help them" -- Jesus contrasts this with his own invitation: Matt 11:28-30: "Come to me, all you who are weary and burdened, and I will give you rest... my yoke is easy and my burden is light." The lawyers\' yoke increases burden; Christ\'s yoke relieves it. The one finger (daktyl&#333; heni = with one finger) recalls the "finger of God" of v.20: they will not lift what the finger of God is lifting.</p>',
'47': '<p>"Woe to you, because you build tombs for the prophets, and it was your ancestors who killed them" -- the practice of commemorating murdered prophets is a form of historical revisionism: we honor those our ancestors murdered. Jesus exposes this as complicity rather than correction: by honoring the tombs, they endorse the deeds. They are about to repeat the pattern -- honoring the murdered prophets while preparing to murder the one greater than all the prophets.</p>',
'48': '<p>"You testify that you approve of what your ancestors did; they killed the prophets, and you build their tombs" -- the logic is prosecutorial: the tomb-builders are co-witnesses to the deeds of their ancestors. Rather than breaking the pattern, they perpetuate it in a more sophisticated form. The prophetic pattern Luke has traced (4:24; 6:23, 26) reaches its culmination: this generation is about to add the Son to the list of the murdered prophets (20:9-16).</p>',
'49': '<p>"Because of this, God in his wisdom said: I will send them prophets and apostles, some of whom they will kill and others they will persecute" -- the pattern of Israel killing God\'s messengers is declared a divine foreknowledge. Acts 7:51-52 (Stephen\'s speech) applies this pattern to its climax: "Was there ever a prophet your ancestors did not persecute? They even killed those who predicted the coming of the Righteous One." The "apostles" Jesus will send anticipates the NT community\'s own persecution.</p>',
'50': '<p>"This generation will be held responsible for the blood of all the prophets that has been shed since the beginning of the world, from the blood of Abel to the blood of Zechariah" -- Abel (Gen 4:8) and Zechariah (2 Chr 24:20-22) bookend the Hebrew canon (Genesis to Chronicles): the first martyr and the last. The generation that kills Jesus inherits the accumulated guilt of all the rejected and murdered prophets. Heb 12:24 uses the same Abel reference with the contrast: "Jesus the mediator of a new covenant, and to the sprinkled blood that speaks a better word than the blood of Abel."</p>',
'51': '<p>"Yes, I tell you, this generation will be held responsible for it all" -- the eschatological accountability of "this generation" (the generation that rejects Jesus) is the culmination of the prophetic-rejection history. The statement is tragic: Jesus weeps over Jerusalem (19:41-44) even as he pronounces its judgment. The accountability-accumulation from Abel to Zechariah and now to the Son of God is the logic of Heb 10:26-31: "If we deliberately keep on sinning after we have received the knowledge of the truth, no sacrifice for sins is left, but only a fearful expectation of judgment."</p>',
'52': '<p>"Woe to you experts in the law, because you have taken away the key of knowledge. You yourselves have not entered, and you have hindered those who were entering" -- the "key of knowledge" (t&#275;n kleida t&#275;s gn&#333;se&#333;s) is the interpretive principle that unlocks the Scriptures as pointing to Christ. The lawyers use it to lock rather than unlock: they prevent both their own entry and others\'. Matt 23:13: "you shut the door of the kingdom of heaven in people\'s faces." The Christological irony: those who should be opening the Scriptures to reveal the Messiah are closing them against him. Rev 3:7: Jesus holds "the key of David," opening what no one can shut.</p>',
'53': '<p>"The Pharisees and the teachers of the law began to oppose him fiercely and to besiege him with questions" -- the fierce opposition (dein&#333;s enechein = to hold intensely against him, passionately hostile) and the questioning barrage (apostomatizein = to question relentlessly, to try to catch him in his words) are the tactics of legal opponents seeking grounds for accusation. The Sanhedrin strategy crystallizes: the goal is no longer to learn from Jesus but to find a charge. This is the beginning of the passion\'s plotting that culminates in 20:19-20 and 22:1-6.</p>',
'54': '<p>"Waiting to catch him in something he might say" (enedreuo ntes auton = laying an ambush for him) -- the ambush language is military: this is not intellectual debate but strategic entrapment. The scribes and Pharisees are now Jesus\'s adversaries in the conflict that will lead to the cross. Luke places this adversarial plotting at the end of the great woe-discourse so the reader sees the direct connection between prophetic confrontation and the establishment\'s murderous response -- the very pattern Jesus had just described (vv.47-51).</p>',
}
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm('mkt-christ', 'luke')
    merge_comm(existing, NEW)
    save_comm('mkt-christ', 'luke', existing)
    import json as _j, pathlib as _pl
    inter = _j.loads((_pl.Path(__file__).parent.parent / 'data/interlinear/luke.json').read_text())
    for ch in [10, 11]:
        ck = str(ch)
        have = set(existing.get(ck, {}).keys())
        need = set(inter.get(ck, {}).keys())
        missing = sorted(int(v) for v in (need - have))
        print(f'  ch{ch}: {len(have)}/{len(need)} -- missing: {missing}')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
